8. sermo . . . oratio. Cp. Quint. xii. 10. 43 Nam mihi aliam quandam videtur habere naturam sermo vulgaris, aliam viri eloquentis oratio. By the first is denoted little more than ‘ conversation ’— a discourse in the language os ordinary life (Cic. Or. §§ 67, 184): oratio implies a higher level of effort, and a more finished style. So Cicero says of the philosophie style ‘ sermo potius quam oratio dicitur' Or. ξ 64.
